    <text id="B0333T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>McDonnell writes a relatively informal letter to Jackson regarding an application
                    for clerks in his division.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Mr. Thos. P. Jackson</name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1867-06-18">June 18th 1867</date>
                        <name type="place">Winchester, <abbr expan="Virginia">Va.</abbr></name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute><abbr expan="Dear">Dr.</abbr> Sir:</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>The money to which you refer was received all right. I will forward an
                    application for clerk with a favorable endorsement. If you have good men for
                    "Registers at large" your Bureau affairs should not be much embarrassed by being
                    chairman of the board. However, you know best what assistance they can render
                    you. <pb n="2"/>Make the application and see what <abbr expan="General"
                    >Genl</abbr> Brown will do.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Truly Yours</salute>
                    <signed>John A. McDonnell</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
